It is kind of minor, in my opinion, to change bankruptcy laws.  What I found most interesting, though, is how this reaffirms that I really fucking hate the Democratic Party.  They should really analyze the dumbass stuff they say if they intend to 'fix' their party.
<br />

<br />
The GOP version that passed, in essence, means that people will pay up to $6,000 over the course of five years if they file bankruptcy.  The Dems, in their elite enlightenment, think this is outrageous; how dare people be held somewhat accountable for their actions.  This amounts to $100 a month.  If <span style="font-style: italic">all</span> of your debt is elminated - except for court ordered payments and student loans - I would think, and hope, that you could scrap together 100 bones a month to pay under this new bill.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">"Americans are going to get thrown into bankruptcy and rather than let out so that they have a new chance and a new opportunity in life because <span style="font-weight: bold">they have done nothing wrong</span>, they're going to be tied up and be paying the credit-card companies for the next five years," said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
<a href="http://www.dfw.com/mld/dfw/11109509.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">LINK</a>
<br />
Sure they did nothing wrong, except run up their credit card bills like morons.  Do people like Kennedy hold so little respect for the common person?  I say this because I get the impression that he thinks "we" are too stupid and must have the government watch out for every little thing, even when it is our own fault.
<br />

<br />
I see the Democrat party just being partisian as hell.  I believe they only argue against these things simply to fight with the GOP.<br />
