			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Part of the credit market is the "risk" that credit issuers take when they give creedit.
<br />

<br />
Money supply is held by a cartel which holds an absolute monopoly.  Money is supplied to this cartel (at the moment) at 1%.  Credit card companies purchase the use of money t this rate and sell it at up to 25%.  This is insane enough.  With massive late fees, credit issuers are raking massive profits already.  It is their responsibility to issue good credit and part of that contract is the ability of the person buying credit the ability to bail out if they go too far.  That is the nature of UNSECURED debt.
<br />

<br />
Banks have been deregulated so that the credit market is more open than it used to be.  Little cedit cards popped up everywhere and everyone started issuing credit to people they should not have.  What the hell... they were only paying 1% and collecting 25 times on the profit.
<br />

<br />
In this order we have:
<br />

<br />
1. An explosion of credit issuers.
<br />
2. Money as cheap as it can get held low for several years.
<br />
3. Bad loans made by these issuers.
<br />
4. Consumers having the rules changed against them in midstream.
<br />

<br />
Unsecured debt is unsecured.  That is the nature of the beast.  Corporations can disolve their liability at will if the venture does not work out.  Suddenly individuals will not be able to?  This new law is severely lopsided.  Banks must be responsible for choosing credit worthy people to loan to.  You cannot indenture fools, and that is exactly what is being set up here.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
