				<div class="postbody">
				The overhaul was nothing more than typical republican pandering to big-business interests, in this case the credit card companies.  Twenty years ago, I was among the first group of college students to be issued an unsecured line of credit.  Back then it wasn't much, $500 - $2000.  The CC companies weren't betting I could ever pay off my balance, they were betting I could make the $25 minimum monthly payment.
<br />

<br />
If bankruptcy was so rampant, that a CC issuer had ever come close to not making a profit (let alone going our of business), some changes might be justified.  As it is, they just want to own you for life.  You're bombarded with advertising every Hallmark holiday about a sale, no-money down, no payments and no interest for one year.  Remember that course you took in high school which helped you learn how to manage your personal finances?  Oh, that's right - we leave that and sex ed to the parents.<br />
